data.content:
xUnit uses **constructors** and **interfaces** instead of attribute-based setup/teardown:

| NUnit | xUnit equivalent |
|-------|-----------------|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` with a fixture class |

Here's the converted code:

```csharp
// Fixture class handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Constructor + IDisposable replace per-test setup/teardown
public class CustomerRepositoryTests
    : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **`IClassFixture<T>`** — xUnit creates `DatabaseFixture` once and shares it across all tests in the class. Inject it via the constructor.
- **Constructor** runs before each test (replaces `[SetUp]`).
- **`IDisposable.Dispose`** runs after each test (replaces `[TearDown]`).
- Assertions also change: `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` → `Assert.NotNull(x)`, etc.

If you need async teardown, implement `IAsyncDisposable.DisposeAsync` instead.
